(42, 11, 13, 43, 4, 10, 10, 'give good gifts unto your children', 'Gift of God and Asking', 'This connection highlights the theme of asking for divine gifts. Both passages emphasize that God gives good gifts, specifically the Holy Spirit and living water, to those who ask.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 13, 20, 1, 23, 23, NULL, 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the giving of the Spirit. Luke 11:13 speaks of the Father giving the Holy Spirit, while Proverbs 1:23 mentions pouring out the Spirit. This connection highlights the divine generosity in bestowing the Spirit upon those who seek it.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 13, 44, 2, 38, 38, 'give the Holy Spirit', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the giving of the Holy Spirit as a gift from God. Luke 11:13 speaks of the Father giving the Holy Spirit to those who ask, while Acts 2:38 promises the gift of the Holy Ghost to those who repent and are baptized.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 13, 43, 7, 37, 39, 'Holy Spirit to them that ask him', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Holy Spirit in both passages. Luke emphasizes that the Father gives the Holy Spirit to those who ask, while John describes the Spirit as living water for believers.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 14, 40, 9, 32, 34, 'the dumb spake', 'Healing of the Dumb Man', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of a dumb man possessed by a devil, resulting in the man speaking after the devil is cast out. The reaction of the people marveling at this miracle is also a common theme.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 14, 40, 12, 22, 24, 'the dumb spake', 'Healing of the Mute and Blind', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of individuals who are dumb, showcasing Jesus'' miraculous power. The amazement of the people in both accounts further highlights the significance of these miracles.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 14, 41, 7, 32, 37, 'the dumb spake', 'Healing of Speech Impediments', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing of those unable to speak. In Luke, the dumb man speaks after the devil is cast out, while in Mark, the deaf man with a speech impediment is healed and speaks plainly.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 15, 40, 9, 34, 34, 'He casteth out devils through Beelzebub', 'Accusation of Demonic Power', 'Both passages emphasize the claim that Jesus casts out devils through Beelzebub, highlighting a common accusation against Him. This connection illustrates the opposition Jesus faced from the Pharisees regarding His authority over demons.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 15, 43, 10, 20, 20, NULL, 'Accusations of Madness and Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of accusations against Jesus regarding his mental state and spiritual authority. Both passages reflect the skepticism and hostility he faced, with references to being possessed or mad.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 15, 40, 10, 25, 25, 'Beelzebub', 'Connection of Accusation Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation of being associated with Beelzebub. In Luke, Jesus is directly accused of casting out devils through Beelzebub, while Matthew reflects on how His disciples may face similar accusations. This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by Jesus and His followers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 15, 41, 3, 22, 30, 'He casteth out devils through Beelzebub', 'Accusation of Beelzebub', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation that Jesus casts out demons through Beelzebub, linking the two accounts of opposition against Him. This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding and blasphemy regarding His divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 15, 42, 11, 18, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Accusation and Response', 'This connection highlights the accusation of casting out devils through Beelzebub in both passages. Both passages emphasize the challenge to the logic of such claims regarding the division of Satan''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 15, 43, 7, 20, 20, NULL, 'Accusations of Demonic Influence', 'This connection highlights the theme of accusations against Jesus regarding demonic possession. Both passages reflect the people''s perception of Jesus as being influenced by evil, with Luke mentioning Beelzebub and John referencing a ''devil.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 16, 46, 1, 22, 22, 'a sign from heaven', 'Demand for Signs in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the desire for signs, with Luke highlighting the request for a sign from heaven and 1 Corinthians noting that the Jews require a sign. This connection highlights a common theme of seeking divine validation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 16, 40, 12, 38, 39, 'sought of him a sign', 'Seeking Signs from Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the request for a sign from Jesus. In Luke, the people are tempting him for a sign, while in Matthew, the scribes and Pharisees explicitly ask for a sign. This connection highlights the theme of skepticism towards Jesus'' authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 16, 40, 16, 1, 4, 'a sign from heaven', 'Seeking Signs from Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the request for a sign from heaven, highlighting the skepticism of the Pharisees and Sadducees. They illustrate a common theme of testing Jesus'' authority and the challenge of recognizing spiritual truths.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 16, 41, 8, 11, 12, NULL, 'Seeking a Sign Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking a sign from heaven, highlighting the skepticism of the Pharisees and others towards Jesus. This connection illustrates a recurring theme of doubt and the demand for miraculous proof in the face of Jesus'' teachings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 16, 43, 6, 30, 30, 'sign from heaven', 'Demand for Signs', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking signs from Jesus. Both passages reflect the people''s desire for miraculous evidence to believe in Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 17, 41, 3, 23, 27, 'Every kingdom divided against itself', 'Division and Unity in Kingdoms', 'Both passages emphasize the concept that a kingdom divided against itself cannot stand. They use similar phrasing to illustrate the consequences of internal division, highlighting the importance of unity. This connection highlights the theme of stability in governance.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 17, 40, 12, 25, 29, 'Every kingdom divided against itself is brought to desolation', 'Division and Unity in Kingdoms', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that a kingdom divided against itself cannot stand. They highlight the consequences of internal conflict, using similar phrasing to convey this theme. Additionally, both passages address the authority of Jesus in casting out demons.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 17, 23, 19, 2, 3, 'Every kingdom divided against itself', 'Division and Conflict in Nations', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of internal conflict leading to destruction. Luke highlights a kingdom divided against itself, while Isaiah describes Egyptians fighting against each other, illustrating the consequences of division.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 17, 23, 9, 20, 21, 'Every kingdom divided against itself', 'Division and Conflict in Communities', 'This connection highlights the theme of internal conflict leading to destruction. Both passages emphasize the consequences of division within groups, whether kingdoms or families, resulting in chaos and dissatisfaction.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 17, 43, 2, 25, 25, NULL, 'Understanding Human Nature', 'This connection highlights the awareness of inner thoughts and motivations. Both passages emphasize knowledge of what is within, whether it be a kingdom''s unity or human nature.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 17, 14, 10, 16, 19, 'Every kingdom divided against itself', 'Division and Rebellion', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of division. Luke highlights that a kingdom divided leads to desolation, while 2 Chronicles illustrates the division of Israel from the house of David, resulting in rebellion.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 17, 14, 13, 16, 17, 'Every kingdom divided against itself', 'Division Leading to Defeat', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of division. In Luke, a divided kingdom faces desolation, while in 2 Chronicles, Israel''s division leads to a great slaughter. This connection highlights the theme of unity versus division in achieving victory.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 18, 40, 12, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Satan''s Division', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of Satan being divided against himself, questioning the stability of his kingdom. This connection highlights the logical reasoning presented in both verses regarding the casting out of demons.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 18, 40, 12, 31, 34, 'how shall his kingdom stand?', 'Connection of Blasphemy and Division', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of blasphemy against the Holy Spirit and the division within Satan''s kingdom. The idea of being ''divided against himself'' in Luke connects to the notion of speaking against the Holy Spirit in Matthew, highlighting the seriousness of such actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 18, 40, 4, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Worship and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of God over evil. In Luke, the question of division in Satan''s kingdom highlights the need for unity in worship, while Matthew underscores the exclusive worship of God, rejecting Satan''s influence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 18, 42, 11, 15, 15, 'cast out devils through Beelzebub', 'Connection of Accusation Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation that Jesus casts out devils through Beelzebub. This connection highlights the challenge to Jesus'' authority and the implications of such claims for the kingdom of Satan.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 18, 59, 3, 5, 8, 'divided against himself', 'Connection of Division and Destruction', 'This connection highlights the destructive nature of division, as seen in Luke''s reference to a divided kingdom leading to downfall, and James'' depiction of the tongue as a fire that can defile and destroy. Both passages emphasize the consequences of internal conflict and unchecked speech.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
